This is interesting, but it's pretty clear the author isn't up to speed on historical armor and combat. One large point is that he's ignoring padding. The allowance he makes for ear-space would, in most cases, already be present and filled up with a padded hood or cap of some sort. A helmet that rests directly on the head is almost useless against any sort of concussive weapon. And given that stone throwers were a thing during ancient battles that is something people figured out fairly early. This also means that ears wouldn't poke out nearly as far from their ear-holes as he's drawing it, and thus would require far less protection.

Then there's the point about exposed muzzles. The human face isn't exactly tiny, either, yet open helmets have been very common throughout history. One simple reason is cost. Closed helmets are more often than not found in possession of wealthy warriors. Roman cavalerists, for instance, used ornate full-face masks. Roman infantry kept their ears open because they needed to hear orders. The helmet was copied from Gauls, I believe. Some Greek helmets also have open ears.

And then there's the problem with anthro's quite likely using their mouths for heat exchange. One reason to not wear a closed helmet for humans is performance. This would likely be worse for anthro's. Not to mention use of senses. One successful tournament duelist always wore an open helmet because it allowed better perception... and he won pretty much every fight he was in.

I kind of like those ear-crests, though.
